oblems at home and decided for my safety and work performance that I should focus on resolving the issues at home because my ‚Äúmind was not where it should be while at work‚Äù. He was absolutely right! My mind was far away constantly thinking about everything that was falling apart in my family. I started employment with the Pender County Sheriffs Office in June of 2007. Things were better at home, I was able to focus on work and my children. My husband decided he wanted to become a Police Officer (he was in the military for 4 years and was medically discharged for PTSD and other various mental and physical issues). He made it through the academy after the 2nd try and applied with Pender County. He applied at various other departments but they sent denial of employment letters. Each time I would check the mail and see a letter from a department he applied at, I would open them. I know it was wrong, but he would be outraged and take his anger out on me if he knew departments were denying him. I would have to deal with it! My husband became employed with the Pender County Sheriffs Office around August of 2007. I worked for the Sheriffs office for about 6 months then Burgaw Police Department offered me a job with more money. I accepted the position. My husband was still working with the Sheriffs Office at that time and I was working at Burgaw Police department full time and Part time at the Sheriffs Office. My husband and I separated shortly after. Things started to get ‚Äúnasty‚Äù between the two of us. He realized I was not coming back and that I was serious about our divorce. A few weeks after, Pender County advised me that I am no longer needed. I was confused. Anytime I was called in because they were short on officers, I was there to take their place. They could always depend on me to come in to work when needed. I did my job, and I did it proudly. Despite the Officer safety issues, despite anything else‚Ä¶.I was always there. I felt my husband had something to 